The lineage of Jesus Christ
The birth of Jesus Christ, the son of David, the son of Abraham:
Ibrahim ibn Ishaq. And Ishaq ibn Ya'qub. And Ya'qub ibn Yehuda and his brothers.
Judah became the father of Perez and Zerah by Tamar. Perez became the father of Hezron. Hezron became the father of Ram.
Aram was the son of Amminadab. Amminadab was the son of Nahshon. Nahshon was the son of Salmon.
Obed the son of Boaz was born to Rahab. Boaz was the father of Obed, who was born to Ruth. Obed was the father of Jesse.
And Jesse the king. And David the king begat Solomon of Tamar.
Solomon was the son of Rehoboam. And Rehoboam was the son of Abijah. And Abijah was the son of Asa.
Ahaziah son of Jehoshaphat. Jehoshaphat son of Joram. Joram son of Ahaziah.
Uzziah was the son of Jotham. Jotham was the son of Ahaz. Ahaz was the son of Hezekiah.
Hezekiah became the father of Manasseh. Manasseh became the father of Amon. Amon became the father of Josiah.
Josiah was born in Judah and his brothers during the Babylonian exile.
And after the captivity in Babylon, Jechoniah begat Salathiel. And Salathiel begat Zerubbabel.
Zorobabel was the son of Abihuḏ. Abihuḏ was the son of Eliyakim. Eliyakim was the son of Azor.
Ezra was the son of Zadok. And Zadok was the son of Ahimaaz. And Ahimaaz was the son of Azor.
Alyud son of Alyeazar. Alyeazar son of Matan. Matan son of Yaakov.
Jacob was the son of Joseph, the husband of Mary, who gave birth to Jesus, who is called the Christ.
All the generations from Abraham to David were fourteen generations; and from David until the carrying away into Babylon fourteen generations; and from the carrying away into Babylon unto Christ fourteen generations. The birth of Jesus Christ was on this wise:
As for the birth of Jesus the Christ, it was this way: When his mother Mary was betrothed to Joseph, before they came together, she was found to be with child of the Holy Spirit.
Yusuf was her husband, and he was righteous, and he did not want to expose her, so he wanted to divorce her secretly.
But while he thought about these things, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream, saying, "Joseph, son of David, do not be afraid to take to you Mary your wife, for that which is conceived in her is of the Holy Spirit."
You will give birth to a son and name him Jesus, because he will save his people from their sins."
This was all done so that what the Lord said through the prophet would be fulfilled, who said:
"Behold, the virgin shall conceive and bear a son, and they shall call his name Immanuel," which means, "God with us."
When Joseph awoke from his sleep, he did as the angel of the Lord had commanded him and took his wife.
He did not know her until she gave birth to her firstborn son. He named him Jesus.
The visit of the Magi
And when Jesus was born in Bethlehem of Judea in the days of Herod the king, behold, there came wise men from the east to Jerusalem
Saying, "Where is the newborn king of the Jews? For we saw his star in the east and have come to worship him."
When Herod the king heard this, he was troubled, and all Jerusalem with him.
So he gathered all the chief priests and scribes of the people, and asked them, "Where was the Christ to be born?"
They said to him, "In Bethlehem of Judea, for this is written through the prophet:
And you, Bethlehem, in the land of Judah, are not the least among the princes of Judah; for out of you shall come a Ruler who will shepherd My people Israel."
Then Herod secretly called for the wise men and found out from them the exact time the star had appeared.
Then he sent them to Bethlehem and said, "Go and search carefully for the child. And when you have found him, bring me word so that I may go and worship him also."
When they heard this from the king, they went. And behold, the star which they had seen in the east went before them, till it came and stood over where the young child was.
When they saw the star, they were overjoyed.
They came to the house and saw the child with his mother Mary. They bowed down and worshiped him. Then they opened their treasures and offered him gifts: gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
Then, when they were told in a dream not to return to Herod, they went back another way to their own country. They fled to Egypt.
And when they had departed, behold, the angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream, saying, "Arise and take the young child and his mother, and flee into Egypt, and stay there until I tell you, for Herod will seek the young child to destroy him."
So he arose and took the boy and his mother by night, and departed to Egypt.
And so there was fulfilled what was spoken by the Lord through the prophet: "Out of Egypt I have called my son."
Then Herod, when he saw that he had been tricked by the wise men, was furious. He sent and killed all the male children in Bethlehem and in all that region who were two years old or under, according to the time that he had ascertained from the wise men.
Then what was said by the prophet Jeremiah was fulfilled:
"A voice was heard in Ramah, weeping and great mourning. Rachel weeps for her children and refuses to be comforted, because they are no more." Return to Nazareth.
When Herod died, an angel of the Lord appeared in a dream to Joseph in Egypt.
"Get up, take the boy and his mother, and go to the land of Israel, for those who were seeking the boy's life are dead."
He got up, took the boy and his mother, and came to the land of Israel.
But when he heard that Archelaus was reigning over Judea in place of his father Herod, he was afraid to go there. But being warned in a dream, he turned aside into the region of Galilee.
And he came and lived in a city called Nazareth, that what was spoken by the prophets might be fulfilled, "He will be called a Nazarene."
John the Baptist paves the way
And in those days, John the Baptist came preaching in the wilderness of Judea
"Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand."
This is what Isaiah the prophet said: "A voice of one calling in the desert, 'Prepare the way for the Lord, make straight paths for him.'"
John wore a garment made of camel hair, with a leather belt around his waist. His food was locusts and wild honey.
Then Jerusalem and all Judea and all the region around the Jordan went out to him, and they were baptized by him in the Jordan River, confessing their sins.
And they relied on him in Jordan, acknowledging their sins.
When he saw many Pharisees and Sadducees coming for his baptism, he said to them, "You brood of vipers, who warned you to flee from the wrath to come?"
Make fruits that are worthy of repentance.
Do not think, 'We have Abraham as our father.' For I tell you that God is able to raise up children to Abraham from these stones.
And now I have put the axe to the root of the trees: every tree therefore that does not bring forth good fruit is cut down, and cast into the fire.
I baptize you with water for repentance, but the one coming after me is more powerful than I, whose sandals I am not worthy to carry. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire.
The one who winnows with the wind in his hand, and will clear his threshing floor, and will gather his wheat into the barn, but the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire." The Baptism of Jesus Christ
Then Jesus came from Galilee to the Jordan to John, to be baptized by him.
But John forbade him, saying, "I need to be baptized by you, and are you coming to me?"
Jesus answered him, "Yes, go, for this is the way it is fitting for us to fulfill all righteousness." Then he allowed him to do it.
When Jesus was baptized, he went up out of the water and behold, the heavens were opened to him, and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove and alighting on him.
And a voice from heaven said, "This is my Son, the Beloved, in whom I am well pleased."
Jesus faces the test
Then Jesus was led up by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil.
After fasting for forty days and forty nights, he finally became hungry.
The tempter came to him and said, "If you are the Son of God, tell these stones to become bread."
He answered and said, "It is written, 'Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceeds out of the mouth of God.'"
Then Iblis took him to the Holy City and stopped him at the wing of the Temple.
He said to him, "If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down, for it is written, 'He will command his angels concerning you, and on their hands they will bear you up, lest you strike your foot against a stone.'"
Jesus said to him, "It is also written: 'You shall not tempt the Lord your God.'"
Then Satan also took him to a very high mountain and showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory.
He said to him, "I will give you all of these if you fall down and prostrate to me."
Then Jesus said to him, "Get behind me, Satan! For it is written, 'You shall worship the Lord your God, and him only shall you serve.'"
Then Satan left him, and angels came and attended him. The beginning of his ministry in Galilee.
When Jesus heard that John had been handed over, he withdrew to Galilee.
He left Nazareth and came and lived in Capernaum, which is by the sea in the region of Zebulun and Naphtali,
To fulfill what was spoken through the prophet Isaiah, who said:
"Land of Zebulun, and land of Naphtali, way of the sea, across Jordan, Galilee of the nations."
The people sitting in darkness saw a great light, and those sitting in the field of death and its shadows were illuminated by the light."
From that time Jesus began to preach, and to say, "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand." The calling of the first disciples
And as Jesus walked by the sea of Galilee, he saw two brethren, Simon called Peter, and Andrew his brother, casting a net into the sea: for they were fishers.
Then he said to them, "Come, follow me, and I will make you fishers of men."
At that time, he left the net and followed him.
Then he went on from there and saw two other brothers, James son of Zebedee, and his brother John, in a boat with Zebedee their father, mending their nets. And he called them.
So they left the ship and their father and followed him. Jesus taught and healed the sick.
Jesus went throughout all Galilee, teaching in their synagogues, preaching the gospel of the kingdom, and healing every disease and every sickness among the people.
The news of him spread throughout all of Syria. They brought to him all the sick people who were suffering from various diseases and ailments, the insane, the epileptics, and the paralyzed, and he healed them.
A large crowd followed him from Galilee, the Decapolis, Jerusalem, Judea, and from beyond the Jordan.
The Sermon on the Mount - The Beatitudes
And when the multitudes saw it, they rose up to the mountain, and when he sat down, his disciples came to him.
So he opened his mouth and taught them, saying:
"Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven."
Blessed are those who mourn, for they will be comforted.
Blessed are the meek, for they will inherit the earth.
Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they will be filled.
Blessed are the merciful, for they shall obtain mercy.
Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called the children of God.
Blessed are those who are persecuted for righteousness' sake, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are you when they insult you and persecute you and utter all kinds of evil against you falsely on my account.
Rejoice and be glad, for your reward is great in heaven, for this is how they persecuted the prophets who were before you. You are the salt of the earth and the light of the world.
"You are the salt of the earth, but if the salt loses its saltiness, how can it be made salty again? It is no longer good for anything, except to be thrown out and trampled underfoot by men."
You are the light of the world. A city set on a hill cannot be hidden.
They do not light a lamp and put it under a bushel, but on a lampstand, and it gives light to all in the house.
Let your light shine before men in such a way that they may see your good works, and glorify your Father who is in heaven. Fulfill the law.
"Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them."
For verily I say unto you, until heaven and earth pass away, not the smallest letter or stroke shall in any way pass away from the Law until all be accomplished.
Whoever breaks one of the least of these commandments and teaches others to do so will be called least in the kingdom of heaven. But whoever does and teaches will be called great in the kingdom of heaven.
For I say unto you, Except your righteousness shall exceed the righteousness of the scribes and Pharisees, ye shall in no case enter into the kingdom of heaven. Anger
"You have heard that it was said to the ancients: 'Do not kill, and whoever kills will be liable to judgment.'
And as for me, I say to you: Whoever is angry with his brother in vain is worthy of judgment, and whoever says to his brother: "Raka," is worthy of the congregation, and whoever says: "O fool," is worthy of the fire of hell.
Then, when you are offering your gift at the altar and there remember that your brother has something against you,
Leave your offering there at the altar, go and be reconciled with your brother first, and then come and offer your gift.
Be quick to forgive your opponent while you are on the road with him, lest he hand you over to the judge, and the judge hand you over to the police, and you end up in prison.
I tell you the truth: do not leave until the last penny is gone! Adultery
"You have heard that it was said to those of old: 'Do not commit adultery.'
And I say to you: Whoever looks at a woman to lust after her has already committed adultery with her in his heart.
If your right eye causes you to stumble, tear it out and throw it away, for it is better for you to lose one of your members than for your whole body to be thrown into hell.
And if your right hand causes you to stumble, then cut it off and cast it away from you, for it is better for you that one of your limbs should perish than that you should be cast into the Fire. Divorce
"It was said: 'Whoever divorces his wife, let him give her a written divorce document.'"
And as for me, I say to you: Whoever divorces his wife except for unchastity (adultery) makes her commit adultery, and whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery. The oath
"You have also heard that it was said to those of old: 'Do not swear falsely, but fulfill your oaths to the Lord.'"
And as for me, I say to you: Do not swear at all, neither by heaven, for it is the throne of God,
It is neither on earth, for it is the footstool of his feet, nor in Jerusalem, for it is the city of the great King.
And do not swear by your head, for you cannot make one hair white or black.
Let your speech be: Yes, yes; no, no. What is more than these is from the evil one. Revenge
"You have heard that it was said: 'An eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth.'
And I say to you, do not resist an evil person. But if anyone slaps you on the right cheek, turn to them the other cheek also.
And if anyone wants to sue you and take your coat, give him your cloak as well.
And if you are forced to go a mile, go two.
If someone asks you, give them. If someone wants to borrow from you, do not refuse. Love your enemies.
"You have heard that it was said: 'Love your neighbor and hate your enemy.'
And I say to you: Love your enemies. Bless those who curse you. Do good to those who hate you, and pray for those who mistreat and persecute you.
To be the children of your Father in heaven, he makes his sun shine on the wicked and the good, and sends rain on the righteous and the unrighteous.
Because if you love those who love you, what credit is that to you? Do not even tax collectors do the same?
And if you greet your brothers only, what more are you doing than others? Do not even the tax collectors do the same?
Be perfect, just as your Father in heaven is perfect.
Charity
"Take care that you do not do your charitable deeds before men, in order to be seen by them; otherwise you have no reward with your Father who is in heaven."
So when you give to the needy, do not blow a trumpet before you, as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and in the streets, that they may be honored by men. Truly, I say to you, they have received their reward!
And as for you, when you give alms, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing.
To make your charity in secret. Your father who sees in secret will reward you openly. Prayer
"And when you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, for they love to stand and pray in the synagogues and on the street corners to be seen by men. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward in full!"
And when you pray, go into your room and shut the door and pray to your Father who is in secret. And your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly.
When you arrive, do not repeat vain words like the nations, for they think that their many words will be answered.
Do not imitate them. For your father knows what you need before you ask him.
"Sanctify Thou us, as Thou hast sanctified Thy name.
Your kingdom come. Your will be done, on earth as it is in heaven.
Our daily bread, give us this day.
And forgive us our sins as we also forgive those who have sinned against us.
And lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil. For yours is the kingdom, the power, and the glory forever. Amen.
If you forgive people their mistakes, your heavenly Father will also forgive you.
And if you do not forgive people their mistakes, neither will your Father forgive your mistakes. Fasting
"And when you fast, do not be like the hypocrites, who are dismal in appearance so that they may show others that they are fasting. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward.
And as for you, when you are silent, anoint your head and wash your face.
To not appear to people as fasting, but to your Father who is in secret. For your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly. Treasures in heaven
"Do not store for yourselves treasures on earth, where moth and rust destroy, and where thieves break in and steal.
But lay up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust doth corrupt, and where thieves do not break through nor steal.
Because where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.
The lamp of the body is the eye: if therefore your eye be single, your whole body shall be full of light.
And if your eye is evil, your whole body will be full of darkness. If the light that is in you is darkness, how great is that darkness!
"No one can serve two masters, for either he will hate the one and love the other, or he will be devoted to the one and despise the other. You cannot serve God and money." God cares for us.
"Therefore I say to you, do not worry about your life, what you will eat or what you will drink, nor for your body, what you will wear. Is not life more than food, and the body more than clothing?"
Look at the birds of the air: they neither sow nor reap nor gather into barns, and yet your heavenly Father feeds them. Are you not of more value than they?
And of you, whoever cares, can add more than one arm's length to his height?
Why do you worry about clothing? Consider the lilies of the field, how they grow! They do not toil or spin.
But I tell you that not even Solomon in all his glory was dressed like one of these.
If God so clothes the grass of the field, which today exists, and tomorrow is thrown into the oven, will he not much more clothe you, O men of little faith?
Do not worry, saying, "What shall we eat?" or "What shall we drink?" or "What shall we wear?"
For all these things the nations are asking, for your heavenly Father knows that you need them all.
But seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness, and all these things will be added to you.
Do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow will worry about its own things. Today has enough trouble of its own.
Condemnation of others
"Do not judge so that you will not be judged."
Because by the judgment you pronounce you will be judged, and by the measure you use it will be measured to you.
Why do you look at the speck of sawdust in your brother's eye and pay no attention to the plank in your own eye?
How can you say to your brother, 'Let me take the speck out of your eye,' while the log is in your own eye?
O hypocrite, first remove the plank from your own eye, and then you will see clearly to remove the speck from your brother's eye!
Do not give what is holy to dogs or throw your pearls before swine, lest they trample them under their feet and turn to attack you. Ask, seek, knock.
Ask and you shall receive. Seek and you shall find. Knock and it shall be opened to you.
For whoever asks receives, and whoever seeks finds, and to him who knocks it will be opened.
What father among you, if his son asks for bread, will give him a stone?
And if a fish asks him, will he give him a snake?
If you, being wicked, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father in heaven give good gifts to those who ask him!
So in everything, do to others what you would have them do to you, for this sums up the Law and the Prophets. The narrow gate
"Enter through the narrow gate. For the gate is wide and the way is broad that leads to destruction, and there are many who enter through it!
The narrowest door and the most difficult path that leads to life, and few are those who find it! The tree and its fruit.
"Beware of false prophets, who come to you in sheep's clothing, but inwardly are ravenous wolves!"
By their fruits you shall know them. Do people pick grapes from thorns, or figs from thistles?
Thus, every good tree produces good fruit, but the bad tree produces bad fruit.
A good tree cannot produce bad fruit, and a bad tree cannot produce good fruit.
Every tree that does not produce good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire.
If you know them by their fruits.
"Not everyone who says to me, 'Lord, Lord!' will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only the one who does the will of my Father who is in heaven."
Many will say to me on that day, 'Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name and cast out demons in your name and do many mighty works in your name?'
Then I will declare to them, "I never knew you! Depart from me, you evildoers!" The wise builders and the foolish builders
"Whoever hears these words of mine and acts on them is like a wise man who built his house on the rock."
The rain came down, the rivers came, the winds blew, and they hit that house, but it didn't fall, because it was built on the rock.
And whoever hears these sayings of mine and does not act upon them is like a foolish man who built his house on sand.
The rain came down, the rivers came, the wind blew, and it hit that house and it fell, and it fell with a great crash!
When Jesus had finished these sayings, the crowds were amazed at his teaching,
Because he taught them as one having authority, and not as the scribes.
Healing a leper
When he came down from the mountain, a large crowd followed him.
And a leper came to him and bowed to him, saying, "Lord, if you want, you can make me clean."
Jesus stretched out his hand and touched him, saying, "I want to. Be clean!" And immediately his leprosy was cleansed.
Then Jesus said to him, "See that you tell no one; but go, show yourself to the priest, and offer the gift that Moses commanded, for a proof to them." The centurion's faith.
And when Jesus came into Capernaum, a centurion came to him, asking him for help.
"He says, 'Sir, my servant is laid up in the house, paralyzed and in great distress.'"
Jesus said to him, "I will come and heal him."
The captain of the hundred replied, "Sir, I am not worthy to have you under my roof, but say the word and my boy will be healed."
"For I also am a man under authority, and I have soldiers under me. And I say to one, 'Go,' and he goes; and to another, 'Come,' and he comes; and to my servant, 'Do this,' and he does it."
When Jesus heard this, he was amazed and said to those who were following him, "I tell you the truth, I have not found anyone in Israel with such great faith!
And I say to you: many will come from the east and the west, and will recline with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of the heavens.
And the sons of the kingdom shall be cast out into outer darkness. There shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth."
Then Jesus said to the centurion, "Go; it shall be done for you as you have believed." And the servant was healed at that very hour.
When Jesus came to Peter's house, he saw his mother-in-law lying ill in bed with a fever.
So he touched her hand, and the fever left her, and she got up and served them.
And when it was evening, many who were demon-possessed were brought to him, and he cast out the spirits with a word, and he cured all who were sick.
In order to fulfill what Isaiah the prophet said: "He took our infirmities and carried our diseases." The price of submission
And when Jesus saw a great multitude about him, he gave commandment to depart unto the other side.
A disciple came and said to him, "Teacher, follow me wherever you go."
Jesus said to him, "Foxes have holes, and birds of the sky have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head."
Another of his disciples said to him, "Lord, please allow me to go and bury my father first."
Jesus said to him, "Follow me, and let the dead bury their own dead." He calmed the storm.
And when he got into the boat, his disciples followed him.
And a great disturbance occurred in the sea, so that the waves covered the ship, and he was asleep.
And his disciples came to him and woke him, saying, "Lord, save us! We are perishing!"
"Then he said to them, 'Why are you so afraid, you men of little faith?' Then he got up and rebuked the winds and the sea, and there was a great calm."
And the people were amazed, saying, "What kind of man is this? For even the winds and the sea obey him!" He cast out the demons.
And when he came to the borders of the Gerasenes, two demoniacs met him, coming out of the tombs, exceeding fierce, so that no man could pass by that way.
And they cried out, saying, "What do we have to do with you, Jesus, Son of God? Have you come here to torment us before the time?"
And there was a large herd of pigs grazing far from them.
So the demons asked him, saying, "If you cast us out, permit us to go into the herd of swine."
So he said to them, "Go." And they went out and entered the herd of pigs, and the whole herd of pigs rushed down the steep bank into the sea and drowned in the water.
The shepherds fled and went into the city, and told everything, and about the case of the madmen.
So the whole city came out to meet Jesus. And when they saw him, they begged him to leave their region.
Healing a paralyzed person
So he got into the boat and crossed over and came to his own city.
And when they brought him who was paralyzed to him, they came to him through the faith they had in him. When Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralytic, "Son, your sins are forgiven."
And some of the scribes said to themselves, "This man is blaspheming!"
Jesus knew their thoughts, and said, "Why do you think evil in your hearts?
Which is easier, to say, "Your sins are forgiven you," or to say, "Rise and walk"?
But that you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins"--then he said to the paralytic, "Rise, take up your bed and go home!"
He got up and went to his house.
When the crowd saw this, they were amazed and praised God, who had given people such authority. The call of Matthew
And as Jesus passed by, he saw a man who was blind from birth. And his disciples asked
While he was reclining in the house, many tax collectors and sinners came and were reclining with Jesus and his disciples.
So when the Pharisees saw it, they said to his disciples, "Why does your teacher eat with tax collectors and sinners?"
When Jesus heard this, he said to them, "Those who are healthy do not need a doctor, but those who are sick do."
So go and learn what this means: ‘I desire mercy, and not sacrifice.’ For I did not come to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance.” The question about fasting
Then John's disciples came to him, saying, "Why do we and the Pharisees fast often, but your disciples do not fast?"
Then Jesus said to them, "Can the groomsmen mourn as long as the bridegroom is with them? But the days will come when the bridegroom is taken away from them, and then they will fast."
No one puts a patch on an old garment with a new piece, because the patch takes from the garment, and the garment becomes worse.
And they do not put new wine into old wineskins, or the skins will burst, the wine will run out, and the skins will be ruined. No, they put new wine into new wineskins, and both are preserved." The raising of Jairus' daughter and the healing of the woman with the issue of blood.
And while he was saying these things, behold, a ruler came, and worshiped him, saying, "My daughter has just died, but come and lay your hand on her, and she will live."
Jesus then got up and followed him, along with his disciples.
And if a bleeding woman, who has been bleeding for twelve years, came from behind him and touched the hem of his garment,
For she said to herself, "If I only touch his garment, I shall be whole."
Jesus turned and saw her. "Daughter, cheer up!" he said. "Your faith has healed you." And the woman was healed at once.
And when Jesus came to the ruler's house and saw the flute players and the crowd making a commotion,
He said to them, "Move aside, the girl is not dead, but asleep." They laughed at him.
When the crowd had left, he entered and took her hand, and the girl stood up.
So the news spread throughout that land. Two blind men were healed.
And as Jesus passed by from there, two blind men followed him, crying out and saying, "Have mercy on us, Son of David!"
And when he came to the house, the blind men came to him, and Jesus said to them, "Do you believe that I am able to do this?" They said to him, "Yes, Lord!"
Then he touched their eyes, saying, "According to your faith be it to you."
And their eyes were opened. Jesus rebuked them, saying, "See, no one knows!"
But they went out and spread it throughout that whole land. Healing a mute
And as they were going out, another mute maniac was brought to him.
When the devil came out, the mute spoke, and the crowds were amazed, saying, "Never has anything like this been seen in Israel!"
But the Pharisees said, "He casts out demons by the ruler of the demons!" Few deeds
Jesus went about all the cities and villages, teaching in their synagogues, preaching the gospel of the kingdom, and healing every disease and every sickness among the people.
And when he saw the crowds, he had compassion on them, for they were troubled and were like sheep without a shepherd.
Then he said to his disciples, "The harvest is plentiful, but the laborers are few."
Ask the Lord of the Harvest to send laborers into his harvest.
